where $n \geq 1$ and 
$a_{i,n}$ are polynomials. Convergent power series $\sum_{i=0} \epsilon^{2i} w^i :\mathbb{R}^2_+ \to \mathbb{R}$ yield analytic isometric immersions of the the half-plane $\mathbb{R}^2_+$ with metric~\eqref{eq:ExpMetric}   into $\mathbb{R}^3$. 

We can access the non small-slope regime by increasing  $\epsilon$. In eq.~\eqref{eq:ExpMetric} this is equivalent to keeping $\epsilon$ fixed, say $\epsilon = 1$ and shifting $y$. For sufficiently small $\epsilon$, the power series for $w,u$ and $v$ converge on $\mathbb{R}^2_+$, so the power series with $\epsilon = 1$ converges on $\mathbb{R}^2_+ + (0,\lambda_0)$ for some shift $\lambda_0$. Increasing $\epsilon$ is equivalent to shifting the domain in the negative-$y$ direction, {\em i.e.}, extending the domain of the isometric immersion with $\epsilon = 1$. Efimov's theorem \cite{efimov1964generation}  thus implies, for any smooth isometric immersion  of $\mathbb{R}^2_+$, a principal curvature  will diverge with increasing $\epsilon$. Amsler's theorem \cite{amsler1955surfaces} suggests that for any $\epsilon > 0$, the isometries will develop a {\em singular edge} in $\mathbb{R}^2$ corresponding to the boundary of the domain where the power series converges. 

With increasing $\epsilon$, the singular edge will first intersect with the half-plane $\mathbb{R}^2_+$ at $(0,0)$, {\em i.e.} where $\left|\partial^2_{yy}w\right|$ attains its maximum. If $\partial^2_{yy}w(0,y)\sim A(y+\epsilon-\epsilon_0)^{-(\beta+1)}$, we can approximate $\epsilon_0$ and $\beta$ by the poles and residues of the Pad\'{e} approximants to the logarithmic derivative $\partial^2_{yy}w(0,0)/\partial_yw(0,0)$ \cite{baker1961application}. In fig.~\ref{fig:DlogPade} we plot the Dlog Pad\'{e} approximants for the case $kl=1$ and find that $\epsilon_0\approx 2.86$ and $\beta=.500158$. This strongly indicates that a curvature diverges as $s^{-\frac{1}{2}}$, where $s$ is the distance to the singular edge. This divergence is consistent with the singular edge of the pseudosphere and other hyperbolic surfaces of revolution.
